cs.DL, cs.IR, cs.HC, cs.CL, cs.SI

The paper discusses a new form of citation analysis that focuses on the cognitive impact of concepts in citing publications. This method can be applied to various fields, but the examples used in the paper are from the field of philosophy of science. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.DL (Digital Libraries) as it deals with the organization, retrieval, and distribution of digital information. The paper also involves information retrieval and natural language processing techniques to analyze the citation contexts, which suggests the sub-category cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as the second likely option. The paper also discusses the impact of concepts on researchers, which relates to the sub-category cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) as it deals with the design and evaluation of interactive systems for human use. The paper also involves analyzing text data, which suggests the sub-category cs.CL (Computation and Language) as the fourth likely option. Finally, the paper discusses the impact of concepts over time and across disciplines, which relates to the sub-category cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it deals with the analysis of social and information networks.
